In this session, you will learn:

1. What are alternative ways to create network structures.
2. What are different options to visualize networks and highlight properties.
3. How to analyse multi-modal networks.

# Types of networks

We up to now already talked about different ways how networks can be constructed. Up to now, we mainly focussed on:

* Interaction between entities
* Co-occurence

However, network analysis and modelling is also fully consistent with other structures, which are often a natural outcome of supervised or unsupervised ML exercises:

* Similarities
* Hirarchies (tree-structures)

## Similarity networks

Since similarity is a relational property between entities, similarity matrices obviously can be modeled as a network. Lets illustrate that at the classican `mtcars` example.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->

```r
mtcars %>% head() 
```

Whe could first run a PCA to reduce the dimensionality of the numerical data.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuY2Fyc19wY2EgPC0gbXRjYXJzWyxjKDE6NywxMCwxMSldICU+JSBcbiAgZHJvcF9uYSgpICU+JVxuICBwcmNvbXAoY2VudGVyID0gVFJVRSAsIHNjYWxlID0gVFJVRSlcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
cars_pca <- mtcars[,c(1:7,10,11)] %>% 
  drop_na() %>%
  prcomp(center = TRUE , scale = TRUE)
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


Next, we could create a distance matrice (using the `dist()`) function.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuY2Fyc19kaXN0IDwtIGNhcnNfcGNhJHggJT4lIGRpc3QobWV0aG9kID0gXCJldWNsaWRlYW5cIikgXG5gYGAifQ== -->

```r
cars_dist <- cars_pca$x %>% dist(method = "euclidean") 
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


La voila. Such a distance matrix representas a relational structure and can be modelled as a network.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuZyA8LSBjYXJzX2Rpc3QgJT4lIFxuICBhcy5tYXRyaXgoKSAlPiVcbiAgYXNfdGJsX2dyYXBoKGRpcmVjdGVkID0gRkFMU0UpIFxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
g <- cars_dist %>% 
  as.matrix() %>%
  as_tbl_graph(directed = FALSE) 
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->



<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuZyA8LSBnICU+JSBzaW1wbGlmeSgpICU+JSBhc190YmxfZ3JhcGgoKVxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
g <- g %>% simplify() %>% as_tbl_graph()
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->



<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuZ1xuYGBgIn0= -->

```r

```

<!-- rnb-text-begin -->



Since the network is based on a distance matrix, we would like to reverse that to get edges representing similarity. Since similarity structures are usually fully connected networks, we probably also want to create some sparsity by deleting lower quantile edge weights.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin  -->

```r
g <- g %E>%
  mutate(weight = max(weight) - weight) %>%
  filter(weight >= weight %>% quantile(0.75)) %N>%
  filter(!node_is_isolated()) %>%
  mutate(community = group_louvain(weights = weight) %>% factor())
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


Lets take a look!


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin  -->

```r
set.seed(1337)
g %>% ggraph(layout = "nicely") + 
  geom_node_point(aes(col = community, size = centrality_degree(weights = weight))) + 
  geom_edge_link(aes(width = weight), alpha = 0.25) +
  scale_edge_width(range = c(0.1, 2)) + 
  geom_node_text(aes(label = name, filter = percent_rank(centrality_degree(weights = weight)) > 0.5), repel = TRUE) +
  theme_graph() + 
  theme(legend.position = 'bottom')
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

## Hierarchy (tree) networks

Hirarchical structures are obviously also relational. The difference is, that the connectivity structure tends to be constraint to other levels.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin  -->

```r
create_tree(20, 3) %>% 
    mutate(leaf = node_is_leaf(), root = node_is_root()) %>% 
    ggraph(layout = 'tree') +
    geom_edge_diagonal() +
    geom_node_point(aes(filter = leaf), colour = 'forestgreen', size = 10) +
    geom_node_point(aes(filter = root), colour = 'firebrick', size = 10) +
    theme_graph()
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-plot-begin eyJoZWlnaHQiOjQzMi42MzI5LCJ3aWR0aCI6NzAwLCJzaXplX2JlaGF2aW9yIjowLCJjb25kaXRpb25zIjpbXX0= -->

<img src="data:image/png;base64," />

<!-- rnb-plot-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


* In addition to real life examples such as organigrams, evolutionary trees etc., many ML models result in tree-structures (eg. decision trees).
* We will at our car example execute a hierarchical clustering, which leads to a tree structure (visualized in the dendogram).

<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->

# Multi-Modal Networks

## Intuition

Now its time to talk about an interesting type of networks, multi-modal. This means, a network has several "modes", meaning connects entities on different conceptual levels. The most common one is a **2-mode** (or **bipartite**) network. Examples could be an Author $\rightarrow$ Paper, Inventor $\rightarrow$ Patent, Member $\rightarrow$ Club network. Here, the elements in the different modes represent different things. 

We can alalyse them in seperation (and sometimes we should), but often its helpful to "project"" them onto one mode. Here, we create a node in one mode by joint association with another mode.

![](https://sds-aau.github.io/SDS-master/00_media/networks_2mode.png){width=500px}

While that sounds simple, it can be a very powerful technique, as I will demonstrate now.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->

```r
## Helper function
el_to_sparse_matrix <- function(data, # the edgelist
                                mode_1, # which variable indicates mode 1
                                mode_2, # which variable indicates mode 2
                                projection = 'none' # If a pojection should be done, possible is 'none', 'mode1', 'mode2' 
                                ){
  
  # Define inputs
  i_input <- data %>% pull({{mode_1}}) 
  j_input <- data %>% pull({{mode_2}}) 
  
  require(Matrix)
  mat <- spMatrix(nrow = i_input %>% n_distinct(),
                  ncol = j_input %>% n_distinct(),
                  i = i_input %>% factor() %>% as.numeric(),
                  j = j_input %>% factor() %>% as.numeric(),
                  x = rep(1, i_input %>% length() ) )
  
  row.names(mat) <- i_input %>% factor() %>% levels()
  colnames(mat) <- j_input %>% factor() %>% levels()
  
  # Projection if necessary
  if(projection == 'mode1'){mat %<>% tcrossprod()}
  if(projection == 'mode2'){mat %<>% crossprod()}  
    
  return(mat)
}
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->

# Case study: Bibliographic networks

## Basics

Lets talk about bibliographic networks. In short, that are networks between documents which cite each others. That can be (commonly) academic publications, but also patents or policy reports. Conceptually, we can see them as 2 mode networks, between articles and their reference. That helps us to apply some interesting metrics, such as:

* direct citations
* Bibliographic coupling
* Co--citations

Interestingly, different projections of this 2-mode network give the whole resulting 1-mode network a different meaning.

![](https://sds-aau.github.io/SDS-master/00_media/networks_biblio.png){width=500px}


I will illustrate more in detail in the following. The example is based on some own work.[^1]

### Bibliographic Coupling

#### Create the graph

* We now need to create a projection of the 2-mode matrix to one of the modes.
* We could do that more efficiently via using the sparse matrix calculation I did before, but for maximum clarity lets do it via a join.
* We will first create the article to article network.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuZWxfYmliIDwtIGVsXzJtICU+JSBsZWZ0X2pvaW4oZWxfMm0sIGJ5ID0gJ3JlZmVyZW5jZXMnKSAlPiVcbiAgcmVuYW1lKGZyb20gPSBFSUQueCwgXG4gICAgICAgICB0byA9IEVJRC55KSAlPiVcbiAgc2VsZWN0KGZyb20sIHRvKSAlPiVcbiAgZmlsdGVyKGZyb20gIT0gdG8pICU+JVxuICBjb3VudChmcm9tLCB0bywgbmFtZSA9ICd3ZWlnaHQnKVxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
el_bib <- el_2m %>% left_join(el_2m, by = 'references') %>%
  rename(from = EID.x, 
         to = EID.y) %>%
  select(from, to) %>%
  filter(from != to) %>%
  count(from, to, name = 'weight')
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->

```r
el_bib %>% head()
```

#### Community detection

* A first obvious thing to do would be a community detection


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuZ19iaWIgPC0gZ19iaWIgJU4+JVxuICBtdXRhdGUoY29tID0gZ3JvdXBfbG91dmFpbih3ZWlnaHRzID0gd2VpZ2h0KSkgXG5gYGAifQ== -->

```r
g_bib <- g_bib %N>%
  mutate(com = group_louvain(weights = weight)) 
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


* Now, we can also create community internal statistics, such as the within-community degree.
* To do so, we use the powerful `morph()` functions of `tidygraph`, which basically let you apply `group_by` style operations on graph structures, where graph calculations are execited on subgraphs.
* That let you e.g. contract nodes, work on the linegraph representation, split communities to separate graphs etc. 


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuZ19iaWIgPC0gZ19iaWIgJU4+JVxuICBtb3JwaCh0b19zcGxpdCwgY29tKSAlPiUgXG4gIG11dGF0ZShjZW50X2Rncl9pbnQgPSBjZW50cmFsaXR5X2RlZ3JlZSh3ZWlnaHRzID0gd2VpZ2h0KSkgJT4lXG4gIG11dGF0ZShjb21fY2VudGVyID0gY2VudF9kZ3JfaW50ID09IG1heChjZW50X2Rncl9pbnQpKSAlPiVcbiAgdW5tb3JwaCgpIFxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
g_bib <- g_bib %N>%
  morph(to_split, com) %>% 
  mutate(cent_dgr_int = centrality_degree(weights = weight)) %>%
  mutate(com_center = cent_dgr_int == max(cent_dgr_int)) %>%
  unmorph() 
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->




<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuZ19iaWIgJU4+JVxuICBhc190aWJibGUoKSAlPiVcbiAgY291bnQoY29tLCBzb3J0ID0gVFJVRSlcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
g_bib %N>%
  as_tibble() %>%
  count(com, sort = TRUE)
```

* Ok, seems like there are too many communities to do something meaningful. 
* Lets restrict it to only only communities with more than 20 members.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuZ19iaWIgPC0gZ19iaWIgJU4+JVxuICBhZGRfY291bnQoY29tLCBuYW1lID0gJ2NvbV9uJykgJT4lXG4gIG11dGF0ZShjb20gPSBpZmVsc2UoY29tX24gPj0gMjAsIGNvbSwgTkEpICkgJT4lXG4gIHNlbGVjdCgtY29tX24pICBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
g_bib <- g_bib %N>%
  add_count(com, name = 'com_n') %>%
  mutate(com = ifelse(com_n >= 20, com, NA) ) %>%
  select(-com_n)  
```

```r
g_bib <- g_bib %N>%
  left_join(data %>% select(EID, title, journal, year, citations), by = c('name' = 'EID')) %>%
  mutate(title = title %>% str_trunc(30))
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->




Lets take a look at the network.





<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin  -->

```r
set.seed(1337)
g_bib %>%
  ggraph(layout = 'graphopt') + 
  geom_edge_link(aes(width = weight,
                     color = .N()$com[from] %>% as.factor()), # Notice that
                alpha = 0.5, 
                show.legend = FALSE) +
      scale_edge_width(range = c(0.5, 2)) + 
  geom_node_point(aes(color = com %>% as.factor(),
                      size = centrality_degree(weight = weight), 
                      alpha = citations)) +
  geom_node_text(aes(label = title, filter = com_center == TRUE), repel = TRUE) +
  theme_graph()   + 
  theme(legend.position = 'bottom') + 
  labs(title = 'Bibliographic Coupling Network',
       subtitle = 'Network Analysis 2015-2020',
       color = 'Community',
       size = 'Degree',
       alpha = 'Citations') 
```

```r
g_cit <- el_cit %>% as_tbl_graph(directed = FALSE) %>% 
  igraph::simplify() %>%
  as_tbl_graph(directed = FALSE)  %N>% 
  filter(!node_is_isolated()) %N>% 
  filter(percent_rank(centrality_degree(weights = weight)) >= 0.5) %N>%
  mutate(com = group_louvain(weights = weight)) %N>%
  morph(to_split, com) %>% 
    mutate(cent_dgr_int = centrality_degree(weights = weight)) %>%
    mutate(com_center = cent_dgr_int == max(cent_dgr_int)) %>%
  unmorph() 
```

* Ok, seems like there are too many communities to do something meaningful. 
* Lets restrict it to only only communities with more than 20 members.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuZ19jaXQgPC0gZ19jaXQgJU4+JVxuICBhZGRfY291bnQoY29tLCBuYW1lID0gJ2NvbV9uJykgJT4lXG4gIG11dGF0ZShjb20gPSBpZmVsc2UoY29tX24gPj0gMTAsIGNvbSwgTkEpICkgJT4lXG4gIHNlbGVjdCgtY29tX24pICBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
g_cit <- g_cit %N>%
  add_count(com, name = 'com_n') %>%
  mutate(com = ifelse(com_n >= 10, com, NA) ) %>%
  select(-com_n)  
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


Lets take a look at the network.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin  -->

```r
set.seed(1337)
g_cit %>%
  ggraph(layout = 'graphopt') + 
  geom_edge_link(aes(width = weight,
                     color = .N()$com[from] %>% as.factor()), # Notice that
                alpha = 0.5, 
                show.legend = FALSE) +
      scale_edge_width(range = c(0.5, 2)) + 
  geom_node_point(aes(color = com %>% as.factor(),
                      size = centrality_degree(weight = weight), 
                      alpha = cent_dgr_int)) +
#  geom_node_text(aes(label = name, filter = com_center == TRUE), repel = TRUE) +
  theme_graph()   + 
  theme(legend.position = 'bottom') + 
  labs(title = 'Bibliographic Coupling Network',
       subtitle = 'Network Analysis 2015-2020',
       color = 'Community',
       size = 'Degree',
       alpha = 'Citations') 
```

```r
g_joint %>% ggraph("bipartite") + 
  geom_edge_link(alpha = 0.25) + 
  geom_node_point(aes(col = type, size = centrality_degree(mode = 'all'))) + 
  geom_node_text(aes(label = name), repel = TRUE) + 
  theme_graph() +
  theme(legend.position = 'none')
```
